Operating System (OS) is a layer between the hardware and the applications.
Windows, Linux, macOS
Linux is a command line operating system based on unix

A central processing unit (CPU)—also called a central processor or main processor—is the most important processor in a given computer
Random-access memory (RAM) is a form of electronic computer memory that can be read and changed in any order, typically used to store working data and machine code.

Kernel Space - The privileged, locked-down core of the OS.
User Space - All standard applications run.

Firewall - A security tool, hardware or software that is used to filter network traffic by stopping unauthorized incoming and outgoing traffic.

####  OS Interfaces  ###
GUI - graphical user interface
what you're most likely used to interacting with
CLI - command line interface
where you enter specific text-based commands to retrieve or manipulate information
